In the Mediterranean Sea, on the island of Gozo, there is a beach called Ir-Ramla l-Ä¦amra. On either side of its red sands, there is a cave. I have been caught between the two caves for the last couple of years, observing how both are being called by the same name.

Sources: Facebook (FB), Flickr (F), Instagram (IG), Shutterstock (S), TripAdvisor (TA), Twitter (T) and other websites (W)

View from Tal Mixta Cave in Gozo, Malta.

View from Calypso's Cave. This is one of the most shot locations in Gozo. 

So if you haven't been there, or been there but didn't take your camera with you, you're free to take this and pretend it's yours :-p.
You can just about spot Calypso Cave on the western side of the bay.
Calypso Cave is said to be the place where Odysseus was a prisoner of love for seven years.
Ramla Bay, Gozo
Calypso's Cave. Odysseus is claimed to have been held captive in this cave as concubine to the nymph Calypso. So what's the problem? Where's the drama?
The views from Calypso Cave in Malta are spectacular.

Inside the cave (now collapsed).

Time has not done this attraction any favours. When I first visited (about 15 years ago) you went down the narrow entrance and had a good "window" looking out to sea and felt the magic of the place. Now, the rocks have tumbled and I can't believe it's a safe place to go. It seems like an accident waiting to happen.
View of Ramla Bay
For safety reasons it has been closed off towards the sea-side, thereby virtually eliminating any view that could be had from down there in the past.
View of Ramla Bay

Calypso Cave is located in Xaghra and overlooks the red sands of Gozo's finest beach, Ramla l-Ä¦amra. This cave is suspected to be the cave referred to by Homer in "The Odyssey". Some are even certain that Gozo is the Island of Ogygia and the cave to be the one where the beautiful nymph Calypso kept Odysseus as a "prisoner of love" for seven years.

It was seven years later and only after Jupiter and Hermes intervened that Calypso allowed him to set sail towards home. It could sound like a sweet excuse he gave his wife, no?

On October 6th 2020, _Instagram_ celebrated its 10 year anniversary. Shortly after the social photo sharing app was launched in October 2010, _Calypso's Cave_ on the Maltese island of Gozo was closed off to the public after a partial collapse due to geological movement. While the â€œstabilisation and conservation projectâ€ announced by the Ministry of Gozo awaits completion, the spectacular cave on the other side of the bay is increasingly being shared as _#calypsocave_.
